RUST + TREE-SITTER 0.26.9 (no DSL, no crate):

1) New crate module codegraph-resolve/src/lexical.rs.

2) Scope extraction (per file, in codegraph-parse pass that already walks the tree):
   struct ScopeId(u32);
   struct Scope { id: ScopeId, kind: ScopeKind, parent: Option<ScopeId>, span: (usize,usize), defs: Vec<LocalDef> }
   enum ScopeKind { Module, Function, Block, Class }
   - Single recursive walk of the tree-sitter Tree. On entering a scope-introducing node (function/closure/block/module per a small per-language node-kind table — reuse the language config you already have for CHA) push a Scope with parent = current. ID = stable hash of (file_id, node.start_byte) so it's byte-identical across runs.
   - On a binding node (param, let/var/const, func decl, import binding) add a LocalDef { name, def_span } to the current scope.

3) Reference collection: each identifier-in-expression-position node -> Reference { name, scope: current_scope, ref_span }.

4) Local resolve (Tier A) — the degenerate one-symbol path-find:
   fn resolve_local(r: &Reference, scopes: &ScopeArena) -> Resolution {
     let mut s = Some(r.scope);
     while let Some(sid) = s {
       let mut hits: Vec<&LocalDef> = scopes[sid].defs.iter().filter(|d| d.name == r.name).collect();
       hits.sort_by_key(|d| d.def_span.0);          // determinism
       match hits.as_slice() {
         [single] => return Resolution::Edge(single.def_span),   // provably unique at nearest scope
         [] => { s = scopes[sid].parent; }                       // climb lexical chain
         _ => return Resolution::Drop(Ambiguous),                // >1 in same scope -> DROP
       }
     }
     Resolution::Drop(Unresolved)   // not found in any enclosing scope -> DROP (feeds may_be_incomplete)
   }
   Emit edge kind = LEXICAL_BINDING (new edge type) only on Resolution::Edge.

5) Import edges (Tier B): build a per-module export table during parse (top-level definitions + explicit export markers). At resolve time, before falling back to CHA T4 global-unique, check: does an explicit import statement in this file bind r.name to exactly one (module, symbol)? If yes and that symbol exists uniquely in the target module's export table -> emit CALL/REF edge to it. If the import is glob, or target export is absent/duplicated -> DROP (let T4 try, then drop).

6) Coverage signal: every Drop variant increments the existing dropped / may_be_incomplete counters — no new telemetry surface.

7) Tests: golden-graph determinism test (parse same commit twice, assert byte-identical edge set incl. new LEXICAL_BINDING edges); shadowing test (inner var shadows outer -> resolves to inner); ambiguity test (two params same name -> DROP, zero edges); cross-file glob-import test (asserts DROP, NOT a guessed edge).

